         <abstract>
            <p>Let $S^2_N$ denote the nonlinear manifold of second order splines defined on $\lbrack 0, 1 \rbrack$ having at most $N$ interior knots, counting multiplicities. We consider the question of unicity of best approximations to a function $f$ by elements of $S^2_N$. Approximation relative to the $L_2\lbrack 0, 1 \rbrack$ norm is treated first, with the results then extended to the best $L_1$ and best one-sided $L_1$ approximation problems. The conclusions in each case are essentially the same, and can be summarized as follows: a sufficiently smooth function $f$ satisfying $f'' &gt; 0$ has a unique best approximant from $S^2_N$ provided either $\log f''$ is concave, or $N$ is sufficiently large, $N \geqslant N_0(f)$; for any $N$, there is a smooth function $f$, with $f'' &gt; 0$, having at least two best approximants. A principal tool in the analysis is the finite dimensional topological degree of a mapping.</p>
          </abstract>
